# BYOK Custom Patches — Survive Nightly Syncs

This repo nightly-syncs from `microsoft/vscode-copilot-chat`. The sync workflow
(`.github/workflows/sync-upstream.yml`) resets tracked files to upstream HEAD
and then runs `.github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh`.

**Any custom code you write directly in source files will be wiped out the next
night unless you also add a patch to that script.**

## When to Add a Patch

Whenever you modify a file that also exists upstream and you want the change to
persist, you MUST add a corresponding patch to
`.github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh`.

Examples of code that MUST be patched:

- Modifications to `src/platform/**` (copilot auth, token management, model fetch)
- Modifications to `src/extension/**` that touch upstream files (agent intent,
  BYOK providers, prompt rendering, etc.)
- `package.json` metadata (name, description, version)
- Any file tracked by upstream

New files you add under a custom directory (e.g. `src/byok-custom/`) are safe —
the sync workflow doesn't touch untracked paths.

## Patch Design Rules

### 1. Idempotency

Every patch MUST be safe to run multiple times. Use a sentinel check:

```js
if (code.includes("BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: my-feature")) {
  console.log("my-feature already present, skipping");
  process.exit(0);
}
```

### 2. Sentinel Markers

Wrap inserted code with comment markers so future reviewers (and the sentinel
check) can find it:

```typescript
// ─── BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: my-feature ──────────────────────────
// Preserved by .github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh. Do not remove.
...your code...
// ─── END BYOK CUSTOM PATCH ──────────────────────────────────
```

### 3. Anchor Robustness

Prefer stable, rarely-changing strings as replacement anchors. Bad anchors are
long multi-line bodies that upstream might tweak. Good anchors:

- Import statements
- Function signatures
- Well-known exported constant names

If an anchor is missing, **log a warning and exit 0** — never fail the sync
workflow over a missing anchor:

```js
if (!code.includes(anchor)) {
  console.warn("WARN: anchor not found — skipping my-feature patch");
  process.exit(0);
}
```

### 4. Prefer Append Over Replace

When adding new exports/helpers, append at EOF rather than inserting in the
middle. EOF appends don't conflict with upstream edits.

When modifying behavior, insert a guard BEFORE the upstream logic rather than
replacing the upstream block entirely — this keeps the patch smaller and makes
upstream evolution less likely to break it.

### 5. Test Before Committing

Always test the patch in both modes:

```bash
# Fresh apply (simulates nightly sync on clean upstream)
git stash push -- <files-you-patched>
bash .github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh
git diff stash@'{0}' -- <files-you-patched>  # should match your manual edit
git stash drop

# Idempotent re-apply
bash .github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh   # should say "already present, skipping"
```

## Workflow Checklist

When making a custom change that touches upstream files:

- [ ] Make the change manually in the source file(s) with sentinel markers
- [ ] Write a corresponding patch in `.github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh`
- [ ] Use `if (code.includes(sentinel)) { skip }` for idempotency
- [ ] Gracefully skip on missing anchors (exit 0, log warning)
- [ ] Test fresh-apply: stash, run script, diff against stash, confirm match
- [ ] Test idempotency: run script twice, confirm second run skips
- [ ] **Bump `package.json → version` by one patch level** (see below)
- [ ] Commit the source changes, the script update, AND `package.json` together

### Version bump — required on every push

Patch 3 bumps `package.json → version` by +1 at CI time. If you push two
commits on the same day without bumping the source version first, both CI
builds produce the **same version number** and VS Code silently refuses to
install the second one ("extension already installed at version X.Y.Z").

**Always run this before committing:**

```bash
node -e "
const fs = require('fs');
const p = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync('package.json', 'utf8'));
const [ma, mi, pa] = p.version.split('.').map(Number);
p.version = \`\${ma}.\${mi}.\${pa + 1}\`;
fs.writeFileSync('package.json', JSON.stringify(p, null, '\t') + '\n');
console.log('bumped to', p.version);
"
bash .github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh 2>&1 | grep "version:"
# Should print: version: X.Y.Z+2  (one higher than what you set)
```

