24. **Patch 24** — Always cache system prompt + tools for Anthropic/Vertex BYOK in `anthropicProvider.ts`, with strict 4-breakpoint budget enforcement that **recursively walks nested content**. Upstream's `addCacheBreakpoints` (`cacheBreakpoints.ts`) distributes the 4-breakpoint Anthropic cache budget bottom-up (tool results → current user → leftover on system), so in multi-tool-call turns the system prompt — the largest stable prefix in the conversation, commonly 10-15K tokens with workspace rules + agent template on Opus — never gets marked and re-bills at full 1x rate every turn. The `tools` array is similarly stable across the agent loop but upstream never caches it at all. Marks both at the BYOK layer, **then counts total breakpoints across system + tools + every message content block (including nested text blocks inside `tool_result.content[]`) and strips the oldest message breakpoints until total ≤ 4**. This patch has been broken twice: v1 added our two unconditionally and failed with `Found 6. (invalid_request_error)`; v2 counted only top-level block `cache_control`s and missed nested ones inside `tool_result.content[]` — `anthropicMessageConverter.ts` line ~107 emits `{ type: 'text', text: ' ', cache_control: ... }` as a nested child of a tool_result, and a flat walker would miss it, producing `Found 5` when MCP tools pushed breakpoints into nested content (more tools = more tool_results = more nested breakpoints). v3 (current) recurses through `content?` arrays. Priority order: system (largest stable prefix) > lastTool (stable, never cached by upstream) > recent message breakpoints (tool results / current user). Oldest-first eviction is safe because later cache breakpoints subsume everything before them anyway. Sentinels used to detect an already-patched file: `locateMessageBreakpoints` AND `const walk = (blocks: unknown)` — both must be present. The patch script also contains an upgrade path: any prior Patch 24 block (v1 or v2) is stripped via regex before the recursive-walker version is re-installed, so users running the nightly sync from any broken state get the fix cleanly. Anthropic prompt caching: writes 1.25x, reads 0.1x → break-even after 2 turns, multi-turn agentic loops save ~70% on the shared prefix. Ref: [docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/prompt-caching](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/prompt-caching).
25. **Patch 25** — Anthropic retry + readable-error resilience in `anthropicProvider.ts`. Without this, `overloaded_error` (HTTP 529 — Anthropic's "capacity pressure" signal that tends to fire in bursts on Vertex Claude Opus), rate limits (429), transient 5xx and network blips all bubble up as raw JSON blobs into the chat UI (`Reason: {"type":"error","error":{"type":"overloaded_error","message":"Overloaded"},...}: Error: {...}`). The direct Anthropic provider has a Vertex failover path for these classifications but VertexAnthropic primaries have nothing to fail over to. Adds two top-level helpers — `extractReadableAnthropicMessage(err)` (parses the nested `error.message` + `error.type` out of the SDK envelope, or falls back to the first line) and `classifyRetryableAnthropicError(err)` (SDK class + 529/429/502/503/504/5xx + node transport codes + payload sniffing for non-SDK errors) — and wraps `_makeRequest`'s stream-create + consume in a try/catch that retries up to 4 times with 5s → 10s → 20s → 40s backoff (cap 60s, 75s cumulative worst case), reports a `LanguageModelThinkingPart` progress message on each retry so the user sees *why* the chat is waiting, and re-throws a clean readable error on final failure. Only retries when `ttft === undefined` so partial responses never get duplicated. Budget is intentionally tighter than Gemini's 6-retry Patch 8 — direct Anthropic has Vertex as a failover, so burning a full Gemini-style budget before failing over is worse UX than a quick retry-then-fallover cycle.
