59. **Patch 59 — Relax the Gemini provider's hard model allowlist on discovery.** Symptom: every new Gemini preview model Google ships stays invisible in both the VS Code "Language Models" settings panel and the in-chat model picker until the upstream Microsoft-curated `_knownModels` list is refreshed. Most recent example: `gemini-3.1-flash-lite-preview` shipped on Vertex AI / Generative Language API but `getAllModels` in `geminiNativeProvider.ts` drops it because the model id isn't in `this._knownModels`. User reports: "I don't see gemini 3.1 flash lite preview under gemini even though my API key can access it." Root cause is `for await (const model of models)` followed by `if (this._knownModels && this._knownModels[modelId]) { modelList[modelId] = this._knownModels[modelId]; }` — anything not on the curated list is silently dropped. **Fix in `src/extension/byok/vscode-node/geminiNativeProvider.ts`:** retain the existing known-models entry as the preferred capability source (so production models keep their hand-tuned `BYOKModelCapabilities`), then for any chat-capable model that Google's `/models` endpoint advertises and we don't have a curated entry for, build a sensible fallback from `Model.displayName`, `Model.inputTokenLimit`, `Model.outputTokenLimit`, and a name-based capability heuristic. Two new `protected` methods on the class: **`_inferGeminiCapabilities(model)`** — gated on `supportedActions?.includes('generateContent')` (authoritative chat-capability signal from Google) with a name-regex fallback when `supportedActions` is missing (some preview models don't populate it). Skips non-chat families (`embedding|aqa|imagen|veo|tts|text-bison|chat-bison|live-2|live-audio`) and any non-Gemini family. Returns: `toolCalling: true` (every modern Gemini chat model supports tools — the curated table already encodes this for every entry), `vision: !/text-only/i.test(id)` (default-on, opt-out for explicit text-only variants), `maxInputTokens: model.inputTokenLimit ?? (isLite ? 1_000_000 : 2_000_000)`, `maxOutputTokens: model.outputTokenLimit ?? 65_536`, `thinking: /gemini-3(\.|-)/i.test(id) || /thinking/i.test(id)` (Gemini 3.x defaults to extended reasoning), and conditionally `supportsReasoningEffort: ['low', 'medium', 'high']` when thinking. **`_humanizeGeminiModelId(id)`** — `models/gemini-3.1-flash-lite-preview` → `Gemini 3.1 Flash Lite Preview` (drops the `models/` prefix, splits on `-`, capitalises each segment), used only when Google doesn't populate `displayName`. **Why false-positive-over-false-negative on the heuristic:** the user can always disable a per-model capability via `chatLanguageModels.json` overrides (`{ vendor: "gemini", configuration: { models: { "gemini-3.1-flash-lite-preview": { vision: false } } } }`), but cannot easily *enable* a missing one once a model is filtered out entirely — better to surface the model with optimistic defaults than to hide it. **Call site:** the existing `if (this._knownModels && this._knownModels[modelId])` block gets a `continue;` and an `else { const inferred = this._inferGeminiCapabilities(model); if (inferred) modelList[modelId] = inferred; }` branch. Idempotency sentinel: `BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: gemini model allowlist relaxation`. **Ordering:** independent of every other Gemini patch (Patch 7 / 8 / 26 / 27 / 33 / 43 / 44). The helpers are `protected` so `VertexGeminiLMProvider` (Patch 27) inherits them and benefits from the same fallback — Vertex's `/models` endpoint returns the same `Model` shape so no override is needed. **Non-goals:** does NOT attempt to detect modality from the model description blob (Google's descriptions are inconsistent — would produce more false negatives than positives); does NOT add a settings-controlled allowlist override (user already controls visibility through `chatLanguageModels.json` model picker show/hide flag); does NOT touch the Anthropic / DeepSeek / OpenAI providers (they have their own allowlist patterns — Anthropic uses Patch 21's capability table, DeepSeek uses Patch 55's `_capabilitiesForUnknown`, OpenAI lets the API decide); does NOT change the cached-models de-dup in `chat.cachedLanguageModels.v2` (orthogonal — handled by `scripts/cleanup-stale-byok-models.mjs`); does NOT bump model IDs into the curated `_knownModels` list (canonical source remains the Microsoft-maintained GitHub feed — this patch is purely additive at the discovery seam).

58. **Patch 58 — DeepSeek V4 DSML tool-call leakage client-side workaround.** Symptom: roughly one in nine `tool_choice=auto + stream=true` DeepSeek V4 turns leaks the model's native DSML (DeepSeek Markup Language) tool-call tokens into `delta.content` as raw text instead of parsing them into structured `tool_calls`. The agent loop then treats `<\uFF5C\uFF5CDSML\uFF5C\uFF5Ctool_calls> <\uFF5C\uFF5CDSML\uFF5C\uFF5Cinvoke name="read_file"><\uFF5C\uFF5CDSML\uFF5C\uFF5Cparameter ...>...</\uFF5C\uFF5CDSML\uFF5C\uFF5Cparameter>...</\uFF5C\uFF5CDSML\uFF5C\uFF5Cinvoke></\uFF5C\uFF5CDSML\uFF5C\uFF5Ctool_calls>` as plain assistant markup — the tool calls never execute and the user sees raw DSML in the chat. Server-side root cause is known: DeepSeek's vLLM/SGLang tool-call parser flushes content too eagerly when a DSML start marker spans multiple chunks in streaming + auto mode (vllm-project/vllm#40801, deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-V3#1244, CherryHQ/cherry-studio#14714). Fixes are in progress upstream (vllm PR #41707, sglang #14695) but not merged everywhere yet. **Client-side fix** in two files: **(A) New canonical helper** `src/extension/byok/common/dsmlToolCallStripper.ts`, installed via `install_byok_file`. Pure TS, no VS Code / SDK imports. Exports `DsmlToolCallStripper` (stateful streaming sanitizer with a passthrough ↔ in-dsml state machine), `parseDsmlPayload(payload)` (pure regex parser), and the open/close marker constants. Per-chunk `process(chunk)` returns `{ text, calls }`: `text` is anything safely outside a DSML block (with the last marker-length-minus-one chars held back so split-marker boundaries don't leak partial prefixes); `calls` is any tool calls fully parsed during the chunk. `flush()` drains residual state at stream end (parses partial DSML payloads best-effort). The `string="true"` / `string="false"` attribute on `<\uFF5C\uFF5CDSML\uFF5C\uFF5Cparameter>` is honoured — `false` triggers `JSON.parse` (so DSML-emitted `1`, `120`, `{"k":"v"}` become real number / number / object values) with a fall-back to literal string when JSON parsing fails. Tool-call ids are minted as `deepseek_dsml_<n>` per stripper instance so the agent loop can reference them in subsequent tool_result messages without collision. **(B) Override** `DeepSeekBYOKLMProvider.provideLanguageModelChatResponse` to wrap the `progress` reporter passed into `_lmWrapper.provideLanguageModelResponse`: any `LanguageModelTextPart` is fed through the stripper, sanitized text is re-emitted as `LanguageModelTextPart`, and extracted DSML calls are re-emitted as `LanguageModelToolCallPart`. All other parts (thinking, real tool calls, etc.) pass through untouched. `flush()` runs in a `finally` block so partial streams (early cancellation, network error mid-DSML) still drain whatever was parseable. Stripper state is per-request — fresh instance per `provideLanguageModelChatResponse` invocation — so concurrent requests never share buffers. **Spec coverage:** `dsmlToolCallStripper.spec.ts` pins 18 cases across two describe blocks: `parseDsmlPayload` (single invoke, parallel invocations, `string="false"` JSON parse, bogus-JSON fallback, omitted `string` attribute defaults to string, empty payload); `DsmlToolCallStripper` (plain text passthrough, single block one-chunk, leading + trailing text preserved, marker split char-by-char, partial-marker prefix held back, parallel invocations parse + emit unique ids, residual-payload flush at stream end, plain `<` not part of marker, multiple separate DSML blocks in one stream, sequential id minting per instance, custom id prefix, no indefinite buffering on `<` chars). All 18 green; all 219 BYOK tests still green. **Ordering:** depends on `deepseekProvider.ts` being installed first (Patch 55) — adds `install_byok_file` entries for the stripper + spec adjacent to the provider's `install_byok_file` block in the patch script. Independent of Patches 31 / 33 / 43 / 44 / 54 / 57. **Non-goals:** does NOT detect or strip DSML from non-DeepSeek providers (the wrapper is provider-local — other providers don't emit DSML and adding the check globally would be wasted CPU); does NOT attempt to "repair" malformed DSML beyond what the regex catches (partial / unclosed markers at stream end fall through to `flush()` which parses what it can); does NOT try to detect the `<\uFF5C\uFF5CDSML\uFF5C\uFF5Cfunction_calls>` variant DeepSeek occasionally emits (rare, hasn't been observed in our logs — if it surfaces, add another marker constant + branch); does NOT change the upstream OpenAI request body (no `tool_choice` forcing, no `stream=false` override — both would hurt UX for the 89% of requests that already work correctly); does NOT add retry on DSML detection (the parse is deterministic from the leaked text, and the model already "decided" what tools to call — re-asking would re-roll the dice for no benefit).

34. **Patch 34** — BYOK Auto language-model provider. Upstream's `copilot/auto` is resolved by `AutomodeService`, which POSTs to the CAPI `auto_mode` endpoint with the Copilot session token to pick a concrete model. That path collapses under the BYOK fake-token substitution from Patch 1: the CAPI request 401s, `resolveAutoModeEndpoint` throws, and the UI surfaces "Language model unavailable" on every turn the user selects Auto — removing the one model-selection affordance people reach for most. There's no upstream hook to swap the resolver (the picker hardcodes `vendor === 'copilot'` for the auto entry). Fix: register a parallel `byokauto` vendor with a single `auto` model via a new `BYOKAutoLMProvider` class (canonical copy under `.github/byok-patches/files/byokAutoProvider.ts`, installed into `src/extension/byok/vscode-node/` by `install_byok_file`). On each request the provider reads `chat.byok.auto.defaultModel` (formatted as `vendor/modelId`, e.g. `vertexgemini/gemini-3.1-pro-preview`), resolves the target via `vscode.lm.selectChatModels({ vendor, id })`, and forwards the request through `model.sendRequest(messages, options, token)` — which re-enters the VS Code LM API and dispatches to the actual BYOK provider's `provideLanguageModelChatResponse`. Response stream parts are reported unchanged through the `progress` reporter, preserving tool-call ids, thinking blocks, and token-usage `DataPart`s (Patch 33) intact. `provideTokenCount` defers to the target's tokenizer so agent budget math stays accurate. This is intentionally the "simple" stage (plan B2): one configured fallback, no classifier. The `_resolveTargetModel` method is a protected seam so the follow-up that wires in `ByokRoutingClassifier` (Patch 30) to pick per-request can swap just that method without touching registration or request plumbing. Self-routing is guarded (`byokauto/auto → byokauto/auto` would infinite-loop). Registration patches `byokContribution.ts` alongside the other vendor providers.

35. **Patch 35** — `chat.byok.auto.defaultModel` setting in `configurationService.ts`. String setting consumed by `BYOKAutoLMProvider` (Patch 34) to pick the delegation target. Empty string (default) now triggers vendor-priority auto-discovery inside the provider (see Patch 39) — no compiled-in `vendor/modelId` fallback anymore — so the setting can stay empty on a fresh install and Auto still resolves. Sits next to the Anthropic fallback settings declared by Patch 12.

39. **Patch 39** — Vendor-priority auto-discovery + forgiving resolution in `BYOKAutoLMProvider` (canonical file, installed by Patch 34's `install_byok_file`). Prior behaviour: empty / malformed / stale `chat.byok.auto.defaultModel` fell back to a compiled-in `vertexgemini/gemini-3.1-pro-preview` default. That broke every install that only has the direct `gemini` vendor configured — `vscode.lm.selectChatModels({ vendor: 'vertexgemini', ... })` returned `[]`, the provider threw, and VS Code surfaced the stock "Language model unavailable" string, defeating the whole point of Patches 34–37. New behaviour: (a) if the setting holds a valid `vendor/modelId` and that model *is* registered, use it; (b) if it's empty, malformed, or points at an un-registered vendor, call unfiltered `vscode.lm.selectChatModels()`, bucket by vendor, and walk `AUTO_DISCOVERY_VENDOR_PRIORITY` (`gemini` → `vertexgemini` → `anthropic` → `vertexanthropic` → anything-but-`byokauto`); within the winning vendor, prefer a model whose id/family matches one of `AUTO_DISCOVERY_MODEL_PREFERENCE` (`gemini-3.1-pro`, `gemini-3-flash`, `claude-sonnet-4`, `claude-haiku`, `gpt-5`, etc.), else first-advertised; (c) only throw if *no* non-`byokauto` model is registered at all, and make that error actionable. Also updates the picker `detail` to `→ auto-discovered (prefers Gemini)` when the setting is empty so users know Auto isn't broken, it's just dynamic. The stale-setting fallthrough (setting points at a vendor the user rotated away from) silently logs and continues rather than failing the turn. Reuses the existing `_resolveTargetModel` seam — B3 classifier-driven routing can still override it. Spec coverage: 6 new tests pinning the vendor priority, within-vendor capability preference, stale-setting fallthrough, and the "no BYOK models at all" error shape. Canonical file update only; no new `apply-byok-patches.sh` block needed because Patch 34 already installs the file verbatim from `.github/byok-patches/files/byokAutoProvider.ts`.

43. **Patch 43 — Cross-provider tool-name resolution in `geminiMessageConverter.ts`.** Switching mid-conversation from Sonnet (or any non-Gemini BYOK provider) to a Gemini BYOK model failed with `HTTP 400 INVALID_ARGUMENT: "Please ensure that the number of function response parts is equal to the number of function call parts of the function call turn."` Root cause: Anthropic's `tool_use.id` is `toolu_01ABCdef…` (no tool name encoded), OpenAI's is `call_XYZ` (same), but the VS Code abstraction only keeps `callId` on `LanguageModelToolResultPart` — not the tool's `name`. The Gemini converter's heuristic `callId.split('_')[0]` was designed for Gemini-native `functionName_timestamp` ids and collapses every Anthropic tool response to `name: 'toolu'`. Gemini validates each `functionResponse.name` against the preceding turn's `functionCall.name`s, so a 3-parallel-`read_file` assistant turn vs a `['toolu','toolu','toolu']` user turn is rejected with the error above — despite the counts being equal. Fix in `src/extension/byok/common/geminiMessageConverter.ts`: pre-walk the transcript in `apiMessageToGeminiMessage`, harvest `(callId → name)` from every `LanguageModelToolCallPart`, and thread the map through `apiContentToGeminiContent`. Exposes `resolveToolName(callId, map)` which looks up the map first and falls back to the legacy split heuristic only when the map has no entry (partial transcripts where the preceding tool_call part was truncated out). Sentinel: `export function resolveToolName` (single check gates all four sub-replacements — helper insertion, signature widening, legacy-split swap, map build + two call-site threads). Missing-anchor paths all `console.warn` + `exit 0` (soft-fail) so the sync workflow never breaks. Spec coverage in `geminiMessageConverter.spec.ts` adds 4 cases: Anthropic `toolu_…` resolves to the real tool name via the map; Gemini-native `functionName_timestamp` ids still work through the fallback; parallel calls with distinct Anthropic ids all resolve correctly; OpenAI `call_…` ids work identically. All 17 tests green (13 pre-existing + 4 new). Complements Patch 17 (Gemini→Anthropic id sanitization) which is the inverse direction.

45. **Patch 45 — `BYOKStubChatEndpoint` last-resort fallback in `renderPromptElementJSON`.** Closes the remaining hole in the Patch 18 BYOK fallback. Patch 18 layered a two-step fallback onto the `copilot-base` lookup inside `renderPromptElementJSON` (first try `getChatEndpoint('copilot-base')`, then try the first of `getAllChatEndpoints()`, otherwise throw), but the terminal throw still fires during the brief window between extension activation and the first BYOK provider finishing its async model registration — every BYOK provider (`GeminiNativeBYOKLMProvider`, `AnthropicLMProvider`, both Vertex variants, `CustomOAIProvider`, etc.) construct their endpoint list lazily via `getAllModels()`, which in turn waits on a live HTTPS call to the vendor's `/models` endpoint (Patch 42 memoises it, but the FIRST call still takes a full round-trip). During that window every tool that pipes its result through `renderPromptElementJSON` (read_file, list_dir, file_search, grep_search, get_errors, the edit tools via codeMapper, every prompt element that uses `LanguageModelTool` JSON rendering) fails with "No chat endpoints available (BYOK fallback in renderPromptElementJSON)", which propagates up as `ChatFetchResponseType.Unknown` → `"Sorry, no response was returned."` — despite the user having a perfectly valid BYOK setup. Symptomatic in logs the first few seconds after a window reload or extension reload, worst on cold machines where the vendor round-trip takes ~800ms+. **Fix, two-file patch wired into `apply-byok-patches.sh` under one `PATCH45_EOF` node block:** **(A) New canonical file** `src/extension/byok/common/byokStubChatEndpoint.ts` — pure TS implementing the full `IChatEndpoint` interface with safe defaults. Properties: `family: 'byok-stub'`, `model: 'byok-stub'`, `modelProvider: 'byok-stub'` (deliberately **not** starting with `gpt-`, `claude-`, `gemini-`, `grok-` so none of the ~30 model-specific branches scattered across the prompt tree fire — `anthropicPrompts.tsx` checks `model.startsWith('claude-opus')`, `gpt51CodexPrompt.tsx` checks `family.startsWith('gpt-5.1') && family.includes('-codex')`, `copilotCLIPrompt.tsx` checks `family.startsWith('grok-code')`, etc.); `modelMaxPromptTokens: 128_000` default (overridable via constructor arg, used by `cloneWithTokenOverride`); `maxOutputTokens: 4096`; `supportsVision: false`; `supportsPrediction: false`; `showInModelPicker: false`; `isFallback: true`; `urlOrRequestMetadata: 'byok-stub://no-endpoint'` (non-routable sentinel). Exposes a private `BYOKStubTokenizer` — pure char-based estimate (`Math.ceil(text.length / 4)` with canonical 3-token role-header overhead from the OAI/MS convention), no `ITokenizerProvider` dependency — used by `acquireTokenizer()`. Network-surface methods (`makeChatRequest`, `makeChatRequest2`, `processResponseFromChatEndpoint`, `createRequestBody`) all throw `Error("BYOKStubChatEndpoint: <method> is not supported (stub endpoint).")` synchronously so a future bug where we actually try to send a request through the stub fails loudly instead of silently returning empty data. `cloneWithTokenOverride(n)` returns a fresh `BYOKStubChatEndpoint(n)`. Installed by `fs.writeFileSync` if absent; idempotency sentinel on the module-header string `"BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: stub chat endpoint for renderPromptElementJSON (Patch 45)"`. **(B) Single-line replacement in `src/extension/prompts/node/base/promptRenderer.ts`** — swap the Patch 18 terminal `throw new Error('No chat endpoints available (BYOK fallback in renderPromptElementJSON)');` for a dynamic `import('../../../byok/common/byokStubChatEndpoint')` + `return new BYOKStubChatEndpoint();`. Dynamic import keeps the stub off the prompt-renderer cold-path so normal-case (copilot-base present OR at least one BYOK endpoint registered) never pays the module-load cost. Anchor is the exact throw line Patch 18 installs, so Patch 45 strictly layers on top of Patch 18 without re-playing any of its edits. Idempotency sentinel on the inline comment `"BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: stub endpoint last-resort (Patch 45)"` in the replacement. **Ordering:** must run after Patch 18 (the throw line is what we anchor on). Independent of Patches 31 / 43 / 44 / 46. **Test coverage:** `src/extension/byok/common/test/byokStubChatEndpoint.spec.ts` pins 17 cases across 4 describe blocks. **Shape:** defaults expose IChatEndpoint-compatible values; `modelMaxPromptTokens` constructor override works; `family` / `model` are deliberately un-model-like; `urlOrRequestMetadata` is the non-routable sentinel. **cloneWithTokenOverride:** returns a fresh stub with new budget and preserved defaults. **Tokenizer:** returns `OutputMode.Raw`; `tokenLength` scales with string length (short < long); text parts read from `.text`; empty string → 0; `countMessageTokens` adds role overhead; `countMessagesTokens` aggregates; `countToolTokens` non-zero for non-empty tool list, zero for empty list. **Network methods:** all four throw synchronously with a `/BYOKStubChatEndpoint/`-matching error message (synchronous throw matches the style of `MockEndpoint` and the existing CAPI endpoints — callers who `await` still see a rejected promise). All 17 tests green, no regressions across the copilotcli / byok / prompts suites (fresh-patched codebase from `git checkout -- promptRenderer.ts && rm byokStubChatEndpoint.ts && bash apply-byok-patches.sh` produces byte-identical output to the manual edits). **Non-goals:** does NOT try to make the stub actually useful for chat requests (that would require synthesising a fake network layer and would mask real configuration errors — loud failure is correct); does NOT localise the tokenizer (its output is a soft ceiling, precision is unimportant); does NOT attempt to pre-register any BYOK provider synchronously at extension startup (that would require invasive restructuring of every provider's constructor and fight VS Code's async registration contract); does NOT short-circuit the `copilot-base` or `getAllChatEndpoints()` lookups when a valid endpoint already exists (the stub is strictly last-resort — if ANY real endpoint is registered it still wins); does NOT change the Patch 18 two-step fallback ordering (copilot-base → first-of-all → stub).

49. **Patch 49 — Object-spread breaks getter-based endpoints in three upstream call sites.** Three upstream sites do `{ ...endpoint, modelMaxPromptTokens: X }` to rebudget an endpoint inline before passing it into `PromptRenderer.create()`: `chatVariables.tsx:502`, `toolCalling.tsx:490` (`sendInvokedToolTelemetry`), and `languageModelAccess.ts:520`. Object-spread copies only OWN ENUMERABLE properties — every getter on the class prototype is silently dropped. `ExtensionContributedChatEndpoint` (used for every non-Copilot vendor in BYOK mode AND for Patch 48's family-fallback substitutions) defines `tokenizer`, `model`, `family`, `version`, `modelProvider`, `modelMaxPromptTokens`, `maxOutputTokens`, etc. as class getters. The spread leaves the resulting plain object with `tokenizer === undefined`, then `PromptRenderer`'s constructor calls `tokenizerProvider.acquireTokenizer(endpoint)` which switch-cases on `endpoint.tokenizer` and throws `Unknown tokenizer: undefined`. Surfaces in the chat as "all my tools are currently failing with a system error (Unknown tokenizer: undefined)" — every `read_file` / `run_in_terminal` / `grep_search` / etc. blows up because tool result rendering walks through this path. Latent for years (the spread pattern only hurts BYOK users) and newly amplified by Patch 48 substituting `ExtensionContributedChatEndpoint` for `copilot-fast` / `copilot-base` lookups. **Fix:** replace all three with `endpoint.cloneWithTokenOverride(X)` — every `IChatEndpoint` already implements this method (`agentIntent.ts:523` and `summarizedConversationHistory.tsx:661` already use it). Preserves the prototype + getters because the method returns a properly-constructed instance instead of a plain spread object. Single `PATCH49_EOF` node block in `apply-byok-patches.sh` with three sub-replacements (A/B/C) each gated by an idempotent sentinel-check on `"BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: object-spread breaks getter-based endpoints (Patch 49)"`. Anchors are the exact pre-patch lines so Patch 49 strictly layers on upstream without re-playing any of its surrounding code. Each missing-anchor branch logs a warning and continues to the next sub-replacement (failure of one site doesn't block the others). **Ordering:** independent of Patches 47 / 48 — touches different files. **Non-goals:** does NOT change `ExtensionContributedChatEndpoint` to use plain own properties (would be invasive across the whole class — `cloneWithTokenOverride` is the upstream-blessed pattern); does NOT add an `acquireTokenizer` fallback in `TokenizerProvider` (would mask the same bug elsewhere — fail loud is correct here).

51. **Patch 51 — Context-Window Breakdown Status Item.** Implements a detailed token usage breakdown visible in the chat panel status row (alongside codebase-index and session-sync entries). Because VS Code core does not expose an API to customize the context-ring popover above the chat input, this patch adds a `ChatStatusItem` named `Context Window`. The item displays `Context: X% (Y / Z)` when collapsed, and expands to show a breakdown by segment: System prompt, Tools, Summarized conversation, Conversation history, and Current message. The implementation adds four canonical files under `.github/byok-patches/files/` (`contextBreakdown.ts`, `contextBreakdownChannel.ts`, `contextWindowStatusItem.ts`, and `contextBreakdown.spec.ts`), installs them via `install_byok_file`, hooks the pure calculator into the prompt pipeline at the end of `toolCallingLoop.ts`, and registers the `ContextWindowStatusItem` in `contributions.ts`.

46. **Patch 46 — Strip echoed `[SYSTEM NOTIFICATION - NOT USER INPUT]` prompt wrapper from Copilot CLI assistant messages.** Follow-up to Patches 43 / 44 addressing the cosmetic fallout of long Copilot-CLI sessions where the assistant's response starts with a verbatim echo of the CLI's own task-notification prompt wrapper — the literal three lines `[SYSTEM NOTIFICATION - NOT USER INPUT]\n This is an automated background-task event, NOT a message from the user.\n Do NOT interpret this as user acknowledgement, confirmation, or response to any pending question.\n\n` followed by the model's actual answer. Source traced to `node_modules/@github/copilot/sdk/dist/cli.js` → helper `ICK(q, K)` which prepends that wrapper to `task-notification` prompts on their way *into* the model so the model doesn't mistake an injected tool result for a new user turn. Empirically Gemini (2.5-pro, 3.1-pro-preview) and occasionally Claude echo the whole wrapper back at the start of their response when the turn is confused or interrupted by a downstream error — the first line then renders as a Markdown heading in the chat UI, every subsequent `#`/`-` inside the echoed payload renders as further headings / list items, and the user sees what looks like a "system notification inside my chatbox." Diagnosed by inspecting the CLI SDK bundle: `rg -n "SYSTEM NOTIFICATION" ~/.vscode/extensions/github.copilot-chat-0.46.24/dist/cli.js` pins the wrapper function, and VS Code logs confirm the text lives in the assistant's stream deltas, not in any UI chrome. **Fix, two-file patch wired into `apply-byok-patches.sh` under one `PATCH46_EOF` node block:** **(A) New helper** `src/extension/chatSessions/copilotcli/common/echoedSystemNotificationStripper.ts` — pure TS, no VS Code / SDK imports, exports `ECHOED_SYSTEM_NOTIFICATION_HEADER` (the exact 3-line constant used as the match target) and a stateful factory `createEchoedSystemNotificationStripper()` returning `{ process(messageId, chunk) → string; flush(messageId) → string }`. Per `messageId` state machine: `buffering` (accumulated bytes are still a valid prefix of the header and shorter than it — hold), `stripped` (buffer reached header length, exact match → drop wrapper, flush remainder, let every later chunk for this messageId flow through unchanged), `passthrough` (buffer diverged from the header prefix OR reached header length without matching → flush accumulated bytes as one chunk, stop buffering for this messageId). `flush(messageId)` drains residual bytes when a message ends mid-buffering (short final message under the decision threshold). Deliberately narrow: only position 0 of each message is eligible — later occurrences inside tool outputs or code fences the model is legitimately quoting are left alone. File is installed by `fs.writeFileSync` if absent, idempotency sentinel `"BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: strip echoed SYSTEM NOTIFICATION header (Patch 46)"` in the helper's own header comment. **(B) Session wiring** in `src/extension/chatSessions/copilotcli/node/copilotcliSession.ts` — three sub-replacements: **B1** widen the `copilotCLITools` import line with an adjacent `import { createEchoedSystemNotificationStripper } from '../common/echoedSystemNotificationStripper';`; **B2** instantiate `const echoStripper = createEchoedSystemNotificationStripper();` immediately after the existing `chunkMessageIds`/`assistantMessageChunks` locals (one stripper per `sendPrompt` turn — lifetime matches the turn so no leaks); **B3** replace the two `assistant.message_delta` + `assistant.message` handlers atomically. The delta handler now calls `echoStripper.process(event.data.messageId, event.data.deltaContent)` and early-returns if the sanitized chunk is empty (still buffering); the message handler first calls `echoStripper.flush(event.data.messageId)` to drain residual bytes (covers the rare short-message case and the edge where streaming produced <HEADER.length bytes before the turn completed), then branches on `chunkMessageIds.has(event.data.messageId)` — chunked branch flushes the residual if non-empty, non-chunked branch runs `echoStripper.process` on the full content. Pre-patch `flushPendingInvocationMessages()` call ordering is preserved so sub-agent markdown still gets captured correctly. Per-file idempotency sentinels: helper file presence + the sentinel string; `"createEchoedSystemNotificationStripper"` import in the session file; `"BYOK Patch 46: drop the echoed"` comment as the handler-replacement gate. **Test coverage:** `src/extension/chatSessions/copilotcli/common/test/echoedSystemNotificationStripper.spec.ts` pins 12 cases — full header as single chunk, header split across many small chunks (7-byte slices), character-by-character splitting, chunk boundaries that land mid-header, immediate pass-through when first chunk clearly doesn't match, pass-through when buffered bytes diverge from header prefix (e.g. `[SYSTEM?`), only-first-occurrence stripping (later echoes inside body remain visible), per-messageId state isolation (one message stripped, another passed through), `flush()` returns residual when message ends mid-prefix, `flush()` no-op after commit or after successful strip, empty-chunk safety, content immediately after the header boundary preserved across chunk boundaries. All 561 existing copilotcli tests still green. **Ordering:** independent of all prior patches — neither depends on nor is depended upon by Patches 31 / 43 / 44. **Non-goals:** does NOT try to pattern-match *every* possible prompt wrapper shape (the CLI SDK currently ships exactly this one; if the shape changes upstream the stripper becomes a no-op, which is the correct failure mode — the model's actual answer still renders, just with the echoed wrapper showing through again); does NOT touch the prompt-side code that generates the wrapper (that's inside a compiled-and-bundled SDK we don't control); does NOT attempt to detect "is this echoed content?" heuristically elsewhere in the response (only position 0 of each assistant message — later occurrences are treated as intentional quotes / code fences); does NOT localise the header constant (the CLI SDK emits English regardless of user locale, confirmed by reading `cli.js`); does NOT alter the transcript persisted via `assistantMessageChunks.push(...)` for anything other than the exact wrapper removal (so follow-up turns see the cleaned text too — identical to what the user saw in the UI).

44. **Patch 44 — Specific user-visible error for Gemini tool-history `INVALID_ARGUMENT` 400s.** Follow-up to Patch 43. Where Patch 43 *repairs* the transcript on the way out to Gemini (cross-provider tool-id resolution + orphan tool-result drop), residual 400 `INVALID_ARGUMENT "function response parts / function call parts"` rejections still surface in a handful of edge cases — notably when an intermediate `functionCall` survives truncation but its sibling got collapsed, or when a code path hand-constructs a transcript and skips `apiMessageToGeminiMessage` entirely. Before this patch those landed as the generic `ChatFetchResponseType.Unknown` → "Sorry, no response was returned." with no hint that (a) this is a transcript-shape issue rather than a model outage, and (b) the right recovery is usually "try again" or "start a new chat", not "switch model". The patch has three sub-steps behind a single `PATCH44_EOF` node block: **(A1)** Insert `export const RESPONSE_TOOL_HISTORY_INVALID = 'Model rejected conversation history (tool-call / tool-response mismatch).'` in `src/platform/chat/common/commonTypes.ts` right after the Patch 31 `RESPONSE_EMPTY_STOP` constant, anchored on that constant's closing sentinel comment. **(A2)** Extend the `ChatFetchResponseType.Unknown` message branch in `getErrorDetailsFromChatFetchError` with an `else if (fetchResult.reason === RESPONSE_TOOL_HISTORY_INVALID)` that returns `l10n.t("The model rejected the conversation history because of a tool-call / tool-response mismatch. This usually happens after switching providers mid-chat or after history was summarised. Please try again — if it keeps happening, start a new chat.")`; the empty-stop branch (Patch 31) and the generic fallback stay unchanged. Anchor is the exact two-arm `if/else` tail Patch 31 leaves in place so Patch 44 strictly *nests inside* Patch 31's edits without re-playing them. **(B1-B3)** `src/extension/byok/vscode-node/geminiNativeProvider.ts`: widen the commonTypes import to add `RESPONSE_TOOL_HISTORY_INVALID`; insert `export function isGeminiToolHistoryInvalidError(err)` right before the existing "Gemini retry resilience" patch header (stable anchor) — it guards on `err instanceof ApiError && err.status === 400 && parsed.error.status === 'INVALID_ARGUMENT' && /function\s+(response\|call)\s+parts/i.test(parsed.error.message)` (deliberately conservative: other `INVALID_ARGUMENT` causes like bad generation_config or bad schema fall through to the generic "no response" branch so we don't mislead users); and in the `catch` block of `doRequest`, compute `taggedReason = !token.isCancellationRequested && isGeminiToolHistoryInvalidError(err) ? RESPONSE_TOOL_HISTORY_INVALID : readableReason` and pass that as `reason` in `pendingLoggedChatRequest.resolve(...)`. The `throw new Error(readableReason, { cause: err })` that follows still uses the raw human-readable message for logs / cause chaining — only the chat-UI surface gets the tagged constant. Per-file idempotency sentinels: `"BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: tool-history invalid detection"` in commonTypes, `"detect Gemini tool-history INVALID_ARGUMENT errors"` plus `"BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: tag tool-history INVALID_ARGUMENT"` in the provider. **Ordering:** must run after Patch 31 (B1/A1 both anchor on Patch 31 output). Independent of Patch 43 — Patch 43 reduces frequency, Patch 44 improves the UX of the remainder. **Test coverage:** `src/extension/byok/vscode-node/test/geminiToolHistoryDetection.spec.ts` pins the detector across 8 cases: canonical phrasing, the `function call parts` variant, unrelated INVALID_ARGUMENT (bad generation_config), non-400 status, 400 with different inner status, non-ApiError inputs, non-JSON body, missing inner message. `src/platform/chat/test/node/chatErrorMessages.spec.ts` pins the message branch across 3 cases: tool-history reason returns the specific message, empty-stop reason still returns Patch 31's message (regression guard), unrelated reason falls through to the generic wording. All 11 tests green, fresh-patched codebase from `git stash` produces identical output to the manual edits. **Non-goals:** does NOT add auto-retry (400 is deterministic), does NOT attempt to "repair" the transcript after the fact (Patch 43 already does that on the way out; residual cases happen because the repair surface is bypassed — fixing the bypass requires invasive changes to every producer and is out of scope here), does NOT touch Anthropic or OpenAI providers (they don't have the same contract and their 400s carry different error shapes), does NOT localise the detector regex (Gemini returns error messages in English regardless of user locale, confirmed across `gemini-2.x` and `gemini-3.x`).

43. **Patch 43 — Cross-provider tool-id resolution + orphan tool-result drop in `geminiMessageConverter.ts`.** Fixes "Sorry, no response was returned." on every turn after switching from Anthropic (Sonnet) / OpenAI / any non-Gemini provider to a Gemini BYOK provider mid-conversation. Root cause is twofold. **(A) Name-mismatch.** Gemini's function-calling contract requires that every `functionResponse.name` in a user turn exactly matches a `functionCall.name` emitted by the model in the preceding turn (count AND names). Anthropic's `tool_use.id` looks like `toolu_01ABCdef…` and OpenAI's looks like `call_AbCdEfGh…` — neither encodes the tool name. When VS Code surfaces the transcript to our BYOK layer, those ids land inside `LanguageModelToolResultPart.callId` with no accompanying tool name. The upstream Gemini converter then does `callId.split('_')[0]` to reconstruct a name (which works for Gemini's own `functionName_timestamp` ids) and collapses every Anthropic response to `name: 'toolu'` and every OpenAI response to `name: 'call'`. Result: a 3-parallel-`read_file` assistant turn (names `['read_file','read_file','read_file']`) followed by a user turn (names `['toolu','toolu','toolu']`) gets rejected by Gemini with HTTP 400 `INVALID_ARGUMENT` "Please ensure that the number of function response parts is equal to the number of function call parts of the function call turn." The error bubbles up through `BYOK GeminiNative error` → `ChatFetchResponseType.Unknown` → the generic "Sorry, no response was returned." message, with no actionable recovery. Observed in logs immediately after model switches ( `ccreq:… | unknown | gemini-3.1-pro-preview | 618ms | [GeminiNativeBYOK]`). **(B) Cardinality-mismatch.** Even with perfect name resolution, Gemini 400s the same way when a user turn's `functionResponse` parts outnumber the model turn's `functionCall` parts — typically when history summarisation / truncation drops the assistant turn that emitted the call but keeps the user's response, leaving an orphan. **Fix, five sub-steps wired into `apply-byok-patches.sh` under one `PATCH43_EOF` node block, single idempotency sentinel on `export function resolveToolName`:** (1) Insert `resolveToolName(callId, callIdToName)` helper right before `apiContentToGeminiContent` — primary path reads from the map, legacy split-on-underscore stays as fallback for partial transcripts. (2) Widen `apiContentToGeminiContent`'s signature to `(..., callIdToName: Map<string,string> = new Map())` with defaulted empty map so direct callers (unit tests) still work. (3) Replace the legacy `functionName = part.callId?.split('_')[0] || 'unknown_function'` line with `functionName = resolveToolName(part.callId, callIdToName)` — single line swap, anchor-replaced. (4) Inside `apiMessageToGeminiMessage`, pre-walk every message before the main conversion loop and populate `callIdToName` from every `LanguageModelToolCallPart` (`callId` + `name`); thread the map into both the Assistant and User branch calls to `apiContentToGeminiContent`. (5) Drop orphans inside the `LanguageModelToolResultPart` branch: `if (callIdToName.size > 0 && part.callId && !callIdToName.has(part.callId)) { continue; }` — gated on `size > 0` so the legacy fallback path stays exercisable by direct callers. (6) Append a second cleanup loop right after the existing model-role empty-parts cleanup that does the same for user-role contents — prunes user turns emptied entirely by orphan drops (e.g. when every response in the turn was a stale orphan). **Why the dual fix instead of name-resolution alone:** history truncation empirically strips ~8% of assistant tool-call turns in long sessions (observed when auto-compaction triggers between turn N and N+1, keeping the tool-result user turn but dropping its sibling assistant turn), so name-resolution alone leaves a ~8% residual error rate after a model switch. Orphan-drop converges on Gemini's invariant regardless of name correctness. **Spec coverage in `geminiMessageConverter.spec.ts` adds 7 cases across two describe blocks.** `Cross-provider tool-id resolution (Patch 43)`: Anthropic `toolu_…` ids resolve to real name (reproduces the original 400), legacy Gemini split still works when the pre-walk map is empty (partial-transcript fallback), N parallel tool calls all resolve correctly (multiset equality asserted), OpenAI `call_…` ids work the same way. `Orphan tool-result drop (Patch 43)`: mixed valid+orphan response keeps only the valid one, all-orphan user turn gets pruned entirely after the drop, pure-fallback path (no tool-call anywhere → `size === 0` → orphan-drop inactive) preserves legacy behaviour. All 20 tests in the suite green. **Non-goals:** this patch does NOT add retry on Gemini 400 (400 is deterministic, retry without transcript repair would burn tokens for the same rejection), does NOT add a user-visible error message distinct from the generic "Sorry, no response was returned." (future Patch 44 adds an INVALID_ARGUMENT-specific message branch in `getErrorDetailsFromChatFetchError`), and does NOT touch the Anthropic or OpenAI converters (their own id-generation is irrelevant here — this is strictly about how the Gemini converter reads ids it didn't mint).

42. **Patch 42 — Cache BYOK `getAllModels` for 24h (with 30s negative cache + in-flight dedup).** Fixes a catastrophic quota-exhaustion loop discovered when a user attempted their first chat on `0.46.21`. Upstream's `AbstractLanguageModelChatProvider.provideLanguageModelChatInformation` calls `this.getAllModels(...)` on every single invocation, and VS Code fires that method on every chat model picker refresh — empirically 10-15 times per second in normal UI activity. Every BYOK provider backed by a live HTTP call (`GeminiNativeBYOKLMProvider.client.models.list()`, `AnthropicLMProvider.anthropic.models.list()`, both Vertex variants by inheritance) ends up hammering the vendor's "list models" endpoint at 600-900 requests per minute. Google AI Studio's quota is 200/min/region; the bucket exhausts within seconds, every subsequent call returns HTTP 429 `RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED`, and "Language model unavailable" surfaces in the chat (symptom: chat hangs at "Working..."). Over ~10 minutes of one session the user's Google project accumulated ~8000 × 429s. Patch memoises `getAllModels` on the abstract provider so every concrete vendor inherits the cache with zero boilerplate. Cache key is `(providerId, djb2-hash(apiKey), silent, JSON(configuration))` so rotating keys or changing config naturally invalidates. Successful results live 24h (vendors ship new models at most monthly); failures cache for 30s so transient 429s don't become retry storms. An in-flight dedup table coalesces parallel callers onto one promise so a burst of refreshes during the first fetch resolves with exactly one network call. Implementation sits in `src/extension/byok/vscode-node/abstractLanguageModelChatProvider.ts`: 2 class-level constants (`_BYOK_MODEL_LIST_TTL_MS = 24h`, `_BYOK_MODEL_LIST_NEGATIVE_TTL_MS = 30s`), 2 instance maps (cache + inflight), 2 private helpers (`_byokHashApiKey`, `_byokModelListCacheKey`), and a rewritten `provideLanguageModelChatInformation` that consults the cache before calling `getAllModels`. Patch block in `apply-byok-patches.sh` uses an idempotency sentinel on `_BYOK_MODEL_LIST_TTL_MS` and anchors on the exact pre-patch method body so the replacement is a single `String.replace`. Spec coverage in new `abstractLanguageModelChatProvider.spec.ts`: 6 cases pinning (1) repeated calls share one `getAllModels` invocation, (2) refetch after 24h, (3) apiKey rotation invalidates, (4) N concurrent callers coalesce to 1 call, (5) errors negative-cached for 30s so the same 429 reused, (6) retry after negative-cache elapses. Uses `vi.spyOn(Date, 'now')` for deterministic time travel. A tiny `CountingProvider` subclass stands in for real vendors so the cache is exercised against the real abstract class without importing `@google/genai` or `@anthropic-ai/sdk`. This is a GENERAL fix — every BYOK provider extending `AbstractLanguageModelChatProvider` (and transitively `AbstractOpenAICompatibleLMProvider`) benefits. Not to be confused with Patch 5 (`modelMetadataFetcher` fake-token bypass), which addresses the upstream Copilot-API model fetch — completely different codepath.

41. **Patch 41** — Unlock the CustomOAI BYOK vendor on VS Code Stable. Upstream ships the `customoai` entry in `package.json → contributes.languageModelChatProviders` with `"when": "productQualityType != 'stable'"`, hiding the "OpenAI Compatible" option from the **Add Models...** picker on Stable (Insiders only). Since this fork is predominantly consumed on Stable and CustomOAI is the single most useful generic escape hatch for OAI-compatible third-party providers (DeepSeek, Groq, Together, Fireworks, local llama.cpp / vLLM servers, any future one-off), gating it behind Insiders defeats the point. The patch parses `package.json`, finds the `customoai` entry, and `delete entry.when` — only if the field is present *and* references `productQualityType` (so an unrelated future `when` clause wouldn't get stripped silently). The provider implementation itself (`customOAIProvider.ts`) is already unconditionally registered in `byokContribution.ts` and works fine on Stable — only the manifest-level `when` was gating the UI entry. Idempotent via `!entry.when` early-return; gracefully skips with a warning if the vendor entry ever disappears upstream. Mirrors the JSON-round-trip style of Patches 14 / 28 / 37 (parse → mutate → `JSON.stringify(pkg, null, "\t")`). Sentinel: absence of the `when` clause on the `customoai` entry.

40. **Patch 40 — Classifier-driven BYOK Auto (B3).** The final stage of the BYOK Auto design. `BYOKAutoLMProvider` can now classify each incoming prompt via the Patch 30 3-tier cascade (Gemini Flash → Vertex Haiku → offline heuristic) and route it through a cost-aware routing table that maps `(complexity, task_type)` to an ordered list of model-family needles. Three concrete pieces. **A) New canonical file `byokAutoRouter.ts`** under `src/extension/byok/common/` (installed by a new `install_byok_file` block in this patch). Pure logic — no VS Code API, no SDK imports — so it compiles in `common/` and is hermetically testable. Exports `routeToTarget(classification, candidates, opts)` which (1) drops `byokauto` itself from the candidate pool (prevents infinite recursion); (2) when `classification.needs_vision` is true, filters to models with `capabilities.imageInput === true` but reopens the pool if that would starve the router (better to let the target surface its own image-unsupported error than "no model available"); (3) walks `table[complexity][task_type]` → `table[complexity]['*']` → `DEFAULT_MODEL_PREFERENCES` → first-of-pool, matching needles case-insensitively against `id` / `family` / `name`. Needles are deliberately bare family names (`sonnet`, `haiku`, `opus`, `flash`, `gemini-3.1-pro`) so the same table matches across direct-API (`claude-haiku-4-5`) and Vertex (`claude-3-5-haiku@20241022`) id shapes. Also exports `mergeRoutingTable(override, base)` with defensive validation — non-object overrides, non-string-array cell values, and arrays-at-root all log-and-ignore so a bad user setting never blocks a chat turn. Spec covers 18 cases pinning rule precedence, vision gating, self-exclusion, needle-match semantics, and malformed-override resilience. **B) Provider wiring in `BYOKAutoLMProvider`** (canonical file already installed by Patch 34). Constructor signature now starts with `byokStorageService: IBYOKStorageService` — `byokContribution.ts` passes `this._byokStorageService` explicitly (mirrors `GeminiNativeBYOKLMProvider` et al.), the patch-script block in Patch 34 updated in lockstep so the nightly sync replays the new signature. `_resolveRouting(messages, token)` dispatches on `chat.byok.auto.routingMode`: `'classifier'` runs the full pipeline with the static path as a safety net (any thrown error → log warn, fall through to `_resolveStaticTarget`); `'static'` keeps Patches 34–39 behaviour verbatim. `_getOrCreateClassifier()` caches a single instance keyed by a cheap credential fingerprint (`g:<key-len>:<prefix>|v:<projectId>:<location>:<key-len>`) so key rotation invalidates reliably but hot-path calls don't round-trip to secrets storage every turn. Classifier construction is a dynamic `import('./byokRoutingClassifier')` so the `@google/genai` + `@anthropic-ai/sdk` + `google-auth-library` load stays off the cold-start path for users on `'static'` mode. `_extractClassificationInput(messages)` pulls the last user message (`prompt`), the previous 4 non-tool messages joined by `\n---\n` and capped at 2000 chars (`recentHistory`), structurally-counted file/symbol references (`vscode/reference*` mime types OR bare `{ uri }` parts), and a structural image detector (`mimeType.startsWith('image/')`). `_resolveViaClassifier` short-circuits the network tiers via `isTrivialPrompt()` (the `KW.trivial` regex exported from `byokRoutingHeuristics.ts` — matches "go" / "yes" / "push" / "continue" etc. that make up ~30-40% of the user's own chat history) and runs heuristic-only for those — still produces a valid `ClassificationResult` with `source: 'heuristic'` / `latencyMs: 0` so the router has what it needs. `_formatRoutingHint(resolution)` extends Patch 38's italic line with classifier telemetry: `_via \`vendor/modelId\` • complexity=moderate, task=code_gen, source=gemini-flash (120ms) • rule=table • topic_changed_\n\n` when routing classifier-driven. **C) Two new ConfigKeys** in `configurationService.ts`: `ByokAutoRoutingMode: 'static' | 'classifier'` (default `'classifier'` — safety net guarantees a working turn even without credentials), `ByokAutoRoutingTable: Record<string, Record<string, string[]>>` (default `{}`, merged into the baked-in `DEFAULT_ROUTING_TABLE`). Declared via the usual anchor-and-replace pattern with idempotency gate on `code.includes("ByokAutoRoutingMode")`. Spec coverage on the provider adds 7 cases: classifier-driven routing picks the right cell; classifier info appears in the routing hint; router returning undefined triggers static fallback (and if static *also* fails, surfaces the Patch-39 error message unchanged); classifier throwing triggers static fallback with `logService.warn` hit; no credentials → classifier not constructed (cold-path import skipped); trivial prompts bypass the classifier entirely (asserted with a classifier whose `classify` throws — any accidental call to Tier 1/2 would blow up the turn); reference counting handles both `mimeType`-tagged and bare-`{ uri }` parts. All 160 BYOK unit tests green after this patch. **F) Picker de-dup fix (follow-up).** After Patch 40 shipped, `BYOK Auto` appeared in the global **Language Models** settings panel but was missing from the **in-chat model selector** at the bottom of the chat box. Root cause traced to VS Code core (`workbench.desktop.main.js`): the chat picker dedupes models by bare `metadata.id` — it seeds a blocked set with the upstream `copilot/auto`'s id (`"auto"`) and then filters out every other model whose `metadata.id === "auto"`, regardless of vendor. Our synthetic model was shipping `id: "auto"`, so it collided and was silently dropped from that picker; the Language Models settings panel was unaffected because it keys on the fully-qualified `vendor/group/id` (`byokauto/auto`). Fix: rename `BYOKAutoLMProvider.modelId` from `'auto'` to `'byok-auto'` (one constant — the vendor stays `byokauto`, the display name stays "BYOK Auto", the family stays `byok-auto`). Self-exclusion in the router is vendor-based (`selfVendorId === 'byokauto'`) so it's unaffected. Added a dedicated regression test (`never advertises id: "auto" because VS Code's chat picker de-dupes by bare metadata.id`) that pins the invariant so a future rename doesn't reintroduce the collision. The `byokauto/auto` user-typo self-reject check in `_resolveStaticTarget` still fires correctly (it matches on vendor, not id). No settings key change, no storage migration — users who set `chat.byok.auto.defaultModel` never typed our model id so no invalidation.

38. **Patch 38** — Declare `chat.byok.auto.showRoutingHint: boolean` setting in `configurationService.ts` and have `BYOKAutoLMProvider` (Patch 34's canonical file) prepend a single italic markdown line (`_via \`vendor/modelId\`_\n\n`) as the first stream part of every response when the setting is on (default `true`). The model picker header stays fixed at "BYOK Auto" regardless of which real model we route to — actively misleading once the B3 classifier starts picking different targets per prompt, and even today it hides whether the delegation actually reached `vertexgemini/gemini-3.1-pro-preview` or fell back to the compiled-in default. A `_logService.trace` line already records the target, but nobody opens the log. The hint is cheap (one text part, ~6 tokens, zero extra LLM calls) and renders as markdown inline above the assistant's reply. Gated behind a setting rather than always-on because some users keep chat transcripts pristine — flip `chat.byok.auto.showRoutingHint` to `false` and the target info stays available in the trace log. The canonical provider file was edited directly (it's installed via `install_byok_file`, no source-tree patch needed there); the only source-tree edit is the setting declaration, which uses the same `defineSetting` anchor-and-replace pattern as Patch 35 and inserts immediately after the `ByokAutoDefaultModel` line so the two Auto settings sit visually together. Idempotency check is `code.includes("ByokAutoShowRoutingHint")`.

37. **Patch 37** — Declare `byokauto` vendor in `package.json` under `contributes.languageModelChatProviders`. Without this manifest entry the VS Code runtime refuses the `lm.registerLanguageModelChatProvider('byokauto', ...)` call from Patch 34 with "Chat model provider uses UNKNOWN vendor byokauto" — the provider is silently dropped, the picker never shows "BYOK Auto", and selecting the entry (if it leaks in via some other code path) surfaces as "model not available". Classic manifest-vs-runtime mismatch: the code exists, the registration attempt runs, but the VS Code LM host gates every registration on a manifest contribution, same way `anthropic` / `vertexanthropic` / `vertexgemini` / all other BYOK vendors are gated. No `configuration` block because `byokauto` owns no credentials — it delegates to whichever real BYOK provider `chat.byok.auto.defaultModel` points at, and that provider's own entry handles the API-key UI. Mirrors Patch 14 (vertexanthropic) and Patch 28 (vertexgemini) exactly — same Node heredoc pattern, same case-normalisation defensive block, same idempotency check via `providers.some(p => p.vendor === 'byokauto')`. Appended to the end of the provider list rather than slotted next to a specific peer because it's not a concrete model family, it's the meta-router.

36. **Patch 36** — Defensive auto-endpoint resolution in `languageModelAccess.ts`. Two edit sites, same root cause as Patch 34: `AutomodeService.resolveAutoModeEndpoint` dies under BYOK. (a) `_provideLanguageModelChatInfo` unconditionally pushes the resolved auto endpoint into `chatEndpoints`; if the resolver throws (e.g. empty `allEndpoints` because Patch 5 neutralises the CAPI model fetch, or 401 because the fake token is rejected), the throw propagates out and nukes the entire copilot-vendor model listing — the picker shows only whatever the BYOK providers have cached. Fix: wrap the resolver call in `try/catch`, skip the push on failure, log a warning. Also widens `defaultChatEndpoint` to `IChatEndpoint | undefined` so the type doesn't lie when `autoEndpoint` is absent — downstream code only reads `defaultChatEndpoint` inside the `chatEndpoints` for-loop, which runs zero iterations when the list is empty, so no dereference happens. (b) `_getEndpointForModel` hits the same resolver when a stale picker UI still has `copilot/auto` selected; replace the raw `await ...resolveAutoModeEndpoint(...)` with a BYOK-aware error path: empty endpoints yield "pick BYOK Auto or a concrete model", otherwise wrap the resolver call and rethrow with an actionable message. Users now get a recoverable error instead of "Language model unavailable".

33. **Patch 33** — Tunnel BYOK token usage to the context-window ring indicator. Spans four files: adds `TokenUsage = 'token_usage'` mime type in `endpointTypes.ts`; emits `result.usage` as a `LanguageModelDataPart(TokenUsage)` after each successful request in `anthropicProvider.ts` (covers VertexAnthropic via inheritance) and `geminiNativeProvider.ts` (covers VertexGemini via inheritance, plus adds the `LanguageModelDataPart` + `CustomDataPartMimeTypes` imports upstream doesn't already bring in); captures the DataPart mid-stream in `extChatEndpoint.ts` and returns it as the real `usage` record instead of the hardcoded `{prompt_tokens: 0, ...}` upstream falls back to. Without this the context-window ring in the chat UI stays empty across every BYOK turn (the visual cue users rely on to know when auto-compaction is about to fire always reads 0%). This exact change shipped as commit `c240d53a8` on Apr 14 but was never codified as a patch, so the Apr 17 nightly sync reverted it — classic "made a custom edit without writing a patch, got wiped" story. All four edits are idempotent (sentinels `BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: token-usage data part` / `BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: context-window usage tunnel` / `BYOK CUSTOM PATCH: emit TokenUsage to context-window ring`) and gracefully skip with a warning if any anchor goes missing. **Bash heredoc gotcha re-learned here** (affects Patch 32 too, which had to be fixed alongside): when writing `node << 'PATCH_EOF' ... PATCH_EOF` blocks via editing tools that escape whitespace, leading indentation that comes through as literal `\t` (backslash-t, 2 bytes) instead of a real tab (0x09) will parse-fail in Node.js with `SyntaxError: Expected unicode escape` — outside a string literal `\t` is invalid. Fix: edit with real tabs directly, or post-process the script to convert leading `\\t` runs inside heredocs to real tabs. Inside JS string literals `\t` is fine, it's only leading-whitespace indentation that breaks.

30. **Patch 30** — BYOK routing classifier (3-tier cascade) in new files under `byok/common/` and `byok/vscode-node/`. Foundation for a BYOK-native auto-router that routes each incoming chat request to the cheapest *capable* model instead of blindly sticking to Opus for trivial asks. The classifier answers five questions per prompt — `complexity` (trivial/simple/moderate/complex), `task_type` (code_gen/debug/refactor/plan/shell/sql/explain/test/chat), `topic_changed`, `needs_vision`, and `confidence` — so the future router can pick Haiku/Flash for trivial/simple work, Sonnet/Gemini-Pro for moderate, and reserve Opus for genuine `plan`/`complex`. Uses a three-tier cascade so no single provider outage silently forces Opus-for-everything: **Tier 1** = user's Google Gemini API key (cheapest, sub-second, preferred); **Tier 2** = Vertex Claude Haiku 3.5 when Tier 1 rate-limits, times out, or errors (independent failure domain — Gemini native API and Vertex share no front-door); **Tier 3** = pure-regex heuristic (`byokRoutingHeuristics.ts`) that always returns a lower-confidence decision so the router can still make progress offline. Tier timeouts are 800ms (primary) / 1500ms (failover) — deliberately tight because the classifier sits on the hot path for every turn; failures fall through to the heuristic rather than stalling the response. Both LLM tiers use `temperature: 0`, 256-token caps, and structured-output mode (Gemini `responseSchema`, Anthropic system-prompt-enforced JSON) so responses are cheap and machine-parseable. A robust JSON extractor (`parseAndValidate`) strips markdown fences, repairs missing fields from the heuristic, coerces out-of-vocab enum values, and clamps `confidence` to `[0,1]` — the classifier never throws on malformed LLM output. Vertex Haiku routing reuses the same Vertex baseURL / OAuth bearer / `streamRawPredict`→`rawPredict` dance as VertexAnthropic (Patch 10/11's infrastructure). Tests use `ClassifierTestOverrides` to stub out the two network calls deterministically — 39 unit tests cover the heuristic vocabulary, JSON-extraction edge cases, and every cascade transition (Tier 1 success, Tier 1 reject → Tier 2, both fail → heuristic, Tier 1 timeout → Tier 2, no keys configured → heuristic only). Pure-types file (`byokRoutingClassifier.types.ts`) and heuristic live in `byok/common/` with zero SDK deps so they can be imported from anywhere; the actual classifier (which pulls `@google/genai`, `@anthropic-ai/sdk`, `google-auth-library`) lives in `byok/vscode-node/`. Canonical copies under `.github/byok-patches/files/` + `install_byok_file` block — no upstream tree touched.

